Unsupervised Learning: Trade&Ahead¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The stock market has consistently proven to be a good place to invest in and save for the future. There are a lot of compelling reasons to invest in stocks. It can help in fighting inflation, create wealth, and also provides some tax benefits. Good steady returns on investments over a long period of time can also grow a lot more than seems possible. Also, thanks to the power of compound interest, the earlier one starts investing, the larger the corpus one can have for retirement. Overall, investing in stocks can help meet life's financial aspirations.

It is important to maintain a diversified portfolio when investing in stocks in order to maximise earnings under any market condition. Having a diversified portfolio tends to yield higher returns and face lower risk by tempering potential losses when the market is down. It is often easy to get lost in a sea of financial metrics to analyze while determining the worth of a stock, and doing the same for a multitude of stocks to identify the right picks for an individual can be a tedious task. By doing a cluster analysis, one can identify stocks that exhibit similar characteristics and ones which exhibit minimum correlation. This will help investors better analyze stocks across different market segments and help protect against risks that could make the portfolio vulnerable to losses.

Objective¶

Trade&Ahead is a financial consultancy firm who provide their customers with personalized investment strategies. They have hired you as a Data Scientist and provided you with data comprising stock price and some financial indicators for a few companies listed under the New York Stock Exchange. They have assigned you the tasks of analyzing the data, grouping the stocks based on the attributes provided, and sharing insights about the characteristics of each group.

Data Dictionary¶

  • Ticker Symbol: An abbreviation used to uniquely identify publicly traded shares of a particular stock on a particular stock market
  • Company: Name of the company
  • GICS Sector: The specific economic sector assigned to a company by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) that best defines its business operations
  • GICS Sub Industry: The specific sub-industry group assigned to a company by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) that best defines its business operations
  • Current Price: Current stock price in dollars
  • Price Change: Percentage change in the stock price in 13 weeks
  • Volatility: Standard deviation of the stock price over the past 13 weeks
  • ROE: A measure of financial performance calculated by dividing net income by shareholders' equity (shareholders' equity is equal to a company's assets minus its debt)
  • Cash Ratio: The ratio of a company's total reserves of cash and cash equivalents to its total current liabilities
  • Net Cash Flow: The difference between a company's cash inflows and outflows (in dollars)
  • Net Income: Revenues minus expenses, interest, and taxes (in dollars)
  • Earnings Per Share: Company's net profit divided by the number of common shares it has outstanding (in dollars)
  • Estimated Shares Outstanding: Company's stock currently held by all its shareholders
  • P/E Ratio: Ratio of the company's current stock price to the earnings per share
  • P/B Ratio: Ratio of the company's stock price per share by its book value per share (book value of a company is the net difference between that company's total assets and total liabilities)

Problem Definition¶

  1. Analyze the data provided
  2. Group the stocks using the attributes provided
  3. Share insights about each of the groups so created

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(df, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=df, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=df, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=df, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        df[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        df[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 2, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=12)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

K-means Clustering¶

In [64]:
# Checking the average distortion for a range of 10 kmeans models fitted to the scaled dataset
clusters = range(1, 11)
meanDistortions = []

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=10)
    model.fit(df_subset_scaled)
    prediction = model.predict(df_subset_scaled)
    distortion = (
        sum(
            np.min(cdist(df_subset_scaled, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1)
        )
        / df_subset_scaled.shape[0]
    )

    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "bx-")
plt.xlabel("k")
plt.ylabel("Average Distortion")
plt.title("Selecting k with the Elbow Method", fontsize=16)

# Calculating the silhouette scores for a range of 2 to 10 clusters
sil_score = []
cluster_list = list(range(2, 11))
for n_clusters in cluster_list:
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, random_state=10)
    preds = clusterer.fit_predict((df_subset_scaled))
    score = silhouette_score(df_subset_scaled, preds)
    sil_score.append(score)
    print("For n_clusters = {}, silhouette score is {}".format(n_clusters, score))

plt.plot(cluster_list, sil_score)
plt.show()

Insights¶

Cluster 0¶

  • This cluster contains 278 securities, almost 82% of the listed stocks.
  • Almost all GICS sectors have majority of their listed equities in this cluster. The only exception is the Energy Sector which has majority of its securities in Cluster 1.
  • These cluster is characterised by a low Estimated Shares outstanding and a negative price per book ratio.
  • All other economic indicators like current price, price change per quarter, cah rato, net income, net cash flow, earnings per share, volatility, ROE and P/E ratio are all moderate. ##### This group of securities could be classified as the moderate performers

Cluster 1¶

  • This cluster contains 27 securities, 22 of which is drawn from the Energy sector. another 3 from the Information Technology sector and 1 each from the Industrials and materials sectors.
  • The stocks here are characterised by negative Net income, Net cash Flow, Earnings per share, and price change per quarter.
  • The stocks have high Return on Equity ROE, high Price per earnings ratio (P/E ratio) and the prices are very volatile.
  • These group of shares have the lowest average current price for all the stocks listed, and their average cash ratio is also low.
  • A high Volatility is high with a negative price change is an indication of rapid loss in value in an equity. ##### The group of securities in this cluster could be classified as the lowest performers amongst the listed equities

Cluster 2¶

  • This cluster contains 11 securities made up of 3 securities from the Financials sector, 2 from Health care, 2 from telecommunications services, and 1 each from Information Technology,Energy, Consumer Staples, and Consumer discretionary sectors.
  • These group of equities are characterised by high Net Income and a high estimated shares outstanding.
  • Negative Net cash Flow and Price per book value
  • Low Volatility and P/E Ratio
  • Moderate Price Change per quarter, Current price, ROE, Cash Ratio, and Earnings per share. ##### This cluster contains securities that could be classified as low to moderate performers

Cluster 3¶

  • This sector contains 24 securities made up of 9 securities from the Health care sector, 6 from Consumer discretionary, 5 from Information Technology and 1 each from Energy, Real Estate, Telecommunications Services and Consumer Staples.
  • They are characterised by very high Current price, price Changeper quarter, Cash ratio, Net cash flow, Earnings per share, and price per Book value.
  • the volatility is moderately high with the highest average price change amongst the listed securities over the last quarter, which is an indication of an equity whose price is continuously appreciating.
  • Net Income is moderate. So also is Price per earnings ratio. The estimated shares outstanding is also moderate. ##### This cluster contains the highest performers amongst the listed equities

Hierarchical Clustering¶

In [82]:
# list of distance metrics
distance_metrics = ["euclidean", "chebyshev", "mahalanobis", "cityblock"]

# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "weighted"]

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        Z = linkage(df_subset_scaled, metric=dm, method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(df_subset_scaled))
        print(
            "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.".format(
                dm.capitalize(), lm, c
            )
        )
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

Observations¶

  • The cophenetic correlation for average linkage basing our metric on euclidian distance is the highest with a score of 0.94, but the clusters do not seem to have enough variability.
  • Whereas the cophenetic correlation for ward linkage is 0.71 but the dendrogram appears to provide better clusters.
  • We will try both of them and settle for the one with the better variability.
  • 5 appears to be the appropriate number of clusters for both linkage methods at a dendrogram distance of 10 for average linkage, and a dendrogram distance of 20 for ward linkage.

Insights¶

  • 4 clusters were identified by the K-Means clustering technique while 5 clusters were distinctly identified by the Hierachical Clustering technique.
  • Looking at the clusters generated by these two clustering techniques, we can observe that the clusters are very similar and they map to each other as follows:
  • K-Means Cluster 0 maps to Hierachical Clustering Cluster 3
  • K-Means Cluster 1 maps to Hierachical Clustering Cluster 4
  • K-Means Cluster 2 maps to Hierachical Clustering Cluster 2

  • K means Cluster 3 maps to Hierachical clustering Cluster 0

  • The two methods were able to group 316 out of 340 securities into similar clusters

  • Even though, the Hierachichal technique cluster 1 is not mapped to any K-Means cluster, looking at the HC cluster profile and the attendant boxplots, we can see that this cluster shares a lot of the characteristics of the HC cluster 4 and could therefore be mapped to Kmeans Cluster 1 like the HC cluster 4. When this is done, then we are able to group 321 out of 340 securities into similar clusters

Which clustering technique took less time for execution?

  • The execution time for both clustering methods is very similar. We know for certain that this is due to the number of observations (340) we are working with. As the number of observations increase, the K-Means clustering method is going to offer a better performance in terms of execution speed over the Agglometrative clustering technique.

Which clustering technique gave you more distinct clusters, or are they the same?

  • The hierachichal clustering method gave a clearer picture of how many clusters we should use just by looking at the dendrogram created by the model.

How many observations are there in the similar clusters of both algorithms?

  • The two methods were able to group 316 out of 340 securities into similar clusters. 321 out of 340 if we map HC cluster 1 to K-Means cluster 1 as described above.

How many clusters are obtained as the appropriate number of clusters from both algorithms?

  • Looking at the dendrograms created by the agglomerative clustering technique, we were able to identify 5 custers at a dendogram distance of 20, whereas we use the KElbowVisualizer and the SilhouetteVisualizer to subjectively arrive at an optimal cluster number for the K-Means clustering technique.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

  • The listed securities have been separated into 4 clusters (we shall treat Clusters 1 & 4 of the hierachical clustering method as 1 for the purpose of alignment with the Kmeans clustering method).The four clusters has been identified as:
  • The high performers
  • The moderate performers
  • The low to moderate performers

  • The low performers

  • An investor, based on their appetite for risk and after due consideration of the interplay between some of the economic indicators could choose which of the clusters to concentrate on in the bid to maximise their earnings in any market condition.

  • Trade & Ahead should also continue with dynamic clustering. This becomes necessary as there is a propensity for securities to move accross clusters as more more equities are added into the mix, coupled with the fact that market conditions and therefore economic indicators are bound to change from time to time. Doing dynamic clustering will improve the accuracy of Trade & Ahead's predictions and therefore their Sell/buy recommendations to their clients.
